<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ861224-0071 </DOCNO><HL> Boeing to LeadLauncher WorkOn Midgetman</HL><DD> 12/24/86</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> BA GT ML CAT GY HPC MTI UIS MD LIT TXI GMAEROSPACE (ARO)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Air Force chose Boeing Co. to head the contractor team building the launcher vehicle for the single-warhead Midgetman missile. The company was awarded a $283.7 million contract to move the vehicle into full development.    Boeing, which will team up with Goodyear Tire andamp; Rubber Co., won the job after a competition with a team made up of Martin Marietta Co. and Caterpillar Inc. The contract decision came several days after the Reagan administration quelled internal opposition to the Midgetman and called for funds to move the $50 billion nuclear weapons program into production.    The Air Force yesterday also awarded three other contracts for the Midgetman, a small ICBM:    --Aerojet Strategic Propulsion Co., a unit of Gencorp Inc., $179 million to develop the second-stage booster for the missile.    --Hercules Inc., $169.5 million to develop the third-stage booster.    --Morton Thiokol Inc., $121.7 million to develop the first-stage booster.    In other contracts awarded yesterday, Unisys Corp. won a $509 million Navy contract for Trident missile navigation systems and support equipment.    McDonnell Douglas Astronautics Co., a unit of McDonnell Douglas Corp., received Navy contracts totaling $69.4 million to develop Dragon missile improvements and to produce shoulder-launched assault weapons.    Litton Industries Inc. was awarded a $47.9 million Navy contract for repair and support services for aircraft navigation equipment.    Rock Island Arsenal was given a $34.2 million Army contract for howitzer parts.    ITT Corp. was awarded an $18.1 million Air Force contract for aircraft landing control equipment.    Mason andamp; Hanger-Silas Mason Co. got a $13.7 million Army contract to operate a munitions plant at Middletown, Iowa.    Texas Instruments Inc. received a $12.3 million Air Force contract for aircraft radars.    General Motors Corp. won a $10.3 million Army contract for cargo vehicles. </TEXT></DOC>